One of the key challenges facing the tea sector in Malawi is climate change. Harsh weather conditions have an impact on tea production by reducing the quantity and quality of tea produced both by smallholders and by tea estates. To improve the status of natural resources, estate owners, smallholders and surrounding communities have to work together in coordinated effort.

The project will be implemented by CEPA, AfES and Greenpop. In the project, CEPA will specifically be responsible for facilitating development and implementation of an advocacy strategy and providing capacity building in advocacy and lobbying; communication, planning, monitoring and evaluation. CEPA will also contribute towards mapping of the natural assets by conducting a baseline study for the project. AfES will be responsible for community mobilization and facilitating implementation of alternative livelihoods strategies. Greenpop will contribute towards development of training materials and facilitating trainings in sustainable natural resource management and good agricultural practices.  Greenpop will also support communications and outreach activities, and the development of training materials to be used for capacity building in natural resources management. The organization will work as a consulting firm in providing support to the implementation of project activities.

Specific objectives of this project are to create awareness on child labor issues within coffee value chains in Erussi Sub County and 2 Sub Counties in Zombo; to develop and test different approaches to identify and remediate child labor; and to strengthen civil society organizations to work with UTZ members to build community engagements on addressing child labor issues for boys and girls.

The aim of this project is to build capacities of civil society organizations CEFORD and UNATU to effectively work with the private sector to address child labour issues with attention to boys and girls in coffee supply chain.

The specific objectives of the project are: 
1.	Build capacity of NSTGA to represent their members (Trusts) according to their needs
2.	Build capacity and mindset of the Trusts to represent their members (M/F farmers) according to their needs and,
3.	Build capacity of female members to become leaders and represent female members’ interests within the Trusts and NSTGA.
The long term objective of this project is that the Tea Association of Malawi (TAML) has adopted a smallholder strategy that fits the needs of male and female smallholders and that these smallholders are supported by TAML, tea estates and communities to implement this strategy

1. Reinforce knowledge promotion and understanding on underlying structures and the roles of men and women within the agricultural value chains and the constraints female group staff, female group members and female group member workers might face. 
2. Reinforce support and follow up through coaching among the network of trainers in their efforts to enhance equal rights, opportunities  to eradicate gender based violence and discrimination. 
3. Plan and facilitate a coaching trajectory with partner’s organization to strengthen behavior, attitude and practices regarding gender integration in their projects and incorporate gender within their M&E system to improve knowledge and methodology in analysis of TOC with a gender perspective. 
4. Reinforce assistance to partner’s organizations to reinforce gender integration in topics such as child labor, climate change as well as in the field of producers group strengthening. 
5. Support promotion of gender integration in RA partners’ advocacy and lobbing strategies. 
6. Support behavior change among RA and partners organizations and farmers’ groups and communities to enhance workplaces that are more inclusive.

The overall project goal is to enable the wage committee of the Malawi 2020 Tea Revitalization Project to deliver on its tasks; 1) develop the wage and living income monitoring process; 2) Keep the Anker Malawi living wage benchmark up to date; 3) Relate the prevailing wages in the Malawi tea sector to international poverty benchmarks; 4) Relate the wage developments to critical local parameters in the Malawian economy; 5) Answer questions from the Malawi Tea 2020 Coalition on measurement for in-kind benefits.

The overall goal is to develop a database containing agricultural baseline information on smallholder tea farmers in Malawi. Two specific goals are to 1) register every smallholder tea plot of the Chizunga Trust, and; 2) to record yields which will help to identify shortcomings and management targets. This will be captured in the database.

TECHNOSERVE & IRC propose to design and implement an improved training model, piloted with 10 cooperatives in the San-Pedro and Abengourou area. Leveraging on the experience of Pro-Planteurs model, we will expand the existing training to incorporate increased learning sessions on best financial practices and gender integration, including the implementation of gender action plans. The pilot initiative will culminate in the development of an improved training model that better addresses key sector challenges, a training facilitator guide, and a monitoring and evaluation approach to be used in future projects at scale.

The overall goal of this study is to identify and recommend, in a specific context and based on an analysis of two preselected coffee farms, business models that allow for the payment of a living wage. In addition, a baseline study will be conducted to monitor progress after the business models have been put into practice.

"This project is a continuation of almost a similar project also funded through the Sector Partnership Program in Malawi with an aim to deliver a living wage for tea workers by the year 2020. The project is contributing to the Living Wage ToC whose main goal is that the gap between wages of tea workers and the living wage is reduced. This includes a reduction between the wages of male and female farmers, and that in-kind benefits for tea workers, male and female meet decency levels.
In addition to making significant contribution to the SP ToC for Malawi, the project also contributes to pillars 2 and 3 in the Malawi Tea 2020 Revitalization Programme which aims to improve the competitiveness of the Malawian tea sector so that workers earn a living wage and smallholders are thriving. "

During the first part of the inception phase of the program (December 2015-March 2016) UTZ Country Representatives / SP focal points, supported by external consultants and UTZ Amsterdam staff, carried out a deeper analysis of the sector(s) and themes proposed for their countries to develop a more focused approach for the SP program. The objective of the Country Scans was “to provide a situational analysis on each sector and theme per country assessing the current state with regards to the relevant thematic SP objectives, clearly formulating the causes of the problem that need addressing and identify opportunities for interventions and provide recommendations on potential partners for these interventions.” The Country Scan documents are based on our own experience in the countries, but also document review, conversations/interviews with experts, key informants including Dutch embassy staff, national and international organizations, and workshop results with many of these actors.

During the second part of the inception phase of the program (April-July 2016) UTZ Country Representatives / SP focal points, supported by external consultants and UTZ Amsterdam staff in drafting the country plans. The purpose of the SP country program plan is to set out a strategic direction for sector change in the country and serves as a framework. This plan clearly states UTZ goals for the country the Theory of Change to guide interventions as well as the budget for said activities. Overall, the SP Country Plan will serve as a guide for the next years, as well as a basis for the year plans that will be formulated for 2017 to 2020.
